1 Data

Risk scores

Calculated from UK Biobank (UKB) for Finngen Data Freeze 5 individuals using the PRS-CS18 pipeline with default parameters. Look separate documentation at XXXX.

Endpoints

  • I9_HYPTENS: Hypertension
  • I9_CVD_HARD: Hard cardiovascular diseases
  • I9_CHD: Major coronary heart disease event
  • I9_STR: Ischaemic Stroke, excluding all haemorrhages.

Copying and preprocessing data

Endpoint and covariate files transfered and unzipped. Columns selected from endpoint file prior to import to r. There was not enough memory to upload full files to R.


#Endpoint file and covariate file copied and unzipped

cp /finngen/library-red/finngen_R5/phenotype_2.0/data/finngen_R5_V2_endpoint.gz /finngen/red/ht_prs/data/
cp /finngen/library-red/finngen_R5/phenotype_2.0/data/R5_cov_pheno_1.0.txt.gz /finngen/red/ht_prs/data/  

gzip -d /finngen/red/ht_prs/data/finngen_R5_V2_endpoint.gz
gzip -d /finngen/red/ht_prs/data/R5_cov_pheno_1.0.txt.gz

#Self written perl-script to extract columns from phenotype file
perl select_columns.pl data/finngen_R5_V2_endpoint data/finngen_R5_V2_HTCVD FINNGENID I9_HYPTENS I9_HYPTENS_AGE I9_CVD_HARD I9_CVD_HARD_AGE I9_CHD I9_CHD_AGE I9_STR I9_STR_AGE FU_END_AGE

#This could be loaded directly to R, but now loading will be faster...
perl select_columns.pl data/R5_cov_pheno_1.0.txt data/R5_cov_pheno_selected FINNGENID batch BL_YEAR cohort SEX_IMPUTED PC1 PC2 PC3 PC4 PC5 PC6 PC7 PC8 PC9 PC10

Loading data

endpoints <- fread("/finngen/red/ht_prs/data/finngen_R5_V2_HTCVD", sep = "\t") 

sbp_prs <- fread("/finngen/red/test/ukb-sbp-both.profile") %>%
  select(IID, SCORE) %>%
  rename(SBP_SCORE=SCORE)

dbp_prs <- fread("/finngen/red/test/ukb-dbp-both.profile") %>%
  select(IID, SCORE) %>%
  rename(DBP_SCORE=SCORE)

covs <- fread("/finngen/red/ht_prs/data/R5_cov_pheno_selected")

Combining data

df <- endpoints %>%
  left_join(sbp_prs, by = c("FINNGENID" = "IID")) %>%
  left_join(dbp_prs, by = c("FINNGENID" = "IID")) %>%
  left_join(covs, by = c("FINNGENID" = "FINNGENID")) 
 
#Removing cases without genetic information and some other preprocessing
df <- df %>%
  filter(!is.na(batch)) %>%  
  mutate_at(c("batch","cohort"),as.factor)

Creating scaled variables

df <- df %>%
  mutate(SBP_SCALED = scale(SBP_SCORE),
         DBP_SCALED = scale(DBP_SCORE))

Dividing to late and early hypertension

df <- df %>%  
  mutate(HT_EARLY = if_else(I9_HYPTENS_AGE >= 55, as.integer(0), I9_HYPTENS),
         HT_LATE  = if_else(I9_HYPTENS_AGE <  55,  as.integer(0), I9_HYPTENS),
         AGE_CAT  = if_else(I9_HYPTENS_AGE <  55, 1,2))

Creating categorical variables

Data was categorized also in Mars et al., Nat.Med. 26, 549-557, (2020).

#Let's add parametric versions of the scores
my_probs = c(0,0.025,0.2,0.8,0.975,1)
my_labels =  c("<2.5%","2.5-20%","20-80%","80-97.5%",">97.5%")

df <- df %>%  
  mutate(
    SBP_CAT = cut(SBP_SCORE, breaks=quantile(df$SBP_SCORE, probs = my_probs), labels=my_labels, include.lowest = T),
    DBP_CAT = cut(DBP_SCORE, breaks=quantile(df$DBP_SCORE, probs = my_probs), labels=my_labels, include.lowest = T)    
  ) 

#Let's create new dataframe for tables with 20-80% as reference. 

df_r <- df %>%
  mutate(
    SBP_CAT = relevel(SBP_CAT, ref = "20-80%"),
    DBP_CAT = relevel(DBP_CAT, ref = "20-80%")
  )

Combined and processed data is written out

saveRDS(df, file = "ht_prs.rds")

2 BP PRSs and hypertension

2.1 Proportional hazard assumption: log log curve

Model by survfit

#SBP
km.sbp <- survfit(Surv(I9_HYPTENS_AGE, I9_HYPTENS) ~ SBP_CAT, data=df)
#print(km.sbp)

#DBP
km.dbp <- survfit(Surv(I9_HYPTENS_AGE, I9_HYPTENS) ~ DBP_CAT, data=df)
#print(km.dbp)

log log curve

cols= c("skyblue", "blue", "black", "red", "salmon")
labels= c("<2.5%","2.5-20%","20-80%","80-97.5%",">97.5%")

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot(km.sbp, fun="cloglog", xlim=c(20,100), main="SBP: log log", xlab="Age", col = cols)
plot(km.dbp, fun="cloglog", xlim=c(20,100), main="DBP: log log", xlab="Age", col = cols)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

These look parallel enough. We can use cox model.

2.2 Cox model: covariate adjusted, continuous score

Running models

#Fitting cox for SBP_SCORE
cx.sbp.cs <- coxph(Surv(I9_HYPTENS_AGE, I9_HYPTENS) ~ SBP_SCALED + SEX_IMPUTED + batch + BL_YEAR + PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 + PC10, data=df)

#Fitting cox for DBP_SCORE
cx.dbp.cs <- coxph(Surv(I9_HYPTENS_AGE, I9_HYPTENS) ~ DBP_SCALED + SEX_IMPUTED + batch + BL_YEAR + PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 + PC10, data=df)

  as.data.frame() %>%

2.6 Restricted mean survival times

Pairwise statistics between reference risk (20-80% quantile) and each other quantile is are calculated. For this purpose we need separate dataframe for each statistic of interest.

Creating dataframes for each cases:

#Run with covariates stalled - only unadjusted analysis is shown.
  covs <- c("SEX_IMPUTED", "BL_YEAR", "PC1", "PC2", "PC3", "PC4", "PC5", "PC6", "PC7", "PC8", "PC9", "PC10")
  #"batch"


#test <- my_extr_cats(cat="SBP_CAT", quant="20-80%", df=df)

q <- c("<2.5%", "2.5-20%", "80-97.5%", ">97.5%" )
df.list.sbp  <-  lapply(q, my_extr_cats, cat="SBP_CAT", covs=covs, df=df)
df.list.dbp  <-  lapply(q, my_extr_cats, cat="DBP_CAT", covs=covs, df=df)

rmst2 is runned for all cases

Unadjusted analysis - with covariates R is slow and output of this package does not include mean ages for adjusted.

#Unadjusted, this works:

rmst0.sbp <- lapply(df.list.sbp, function(x) rmst2(x$I9_HYPTENS_AGE, x$I9_HYPTENS, x$CAT, tau=95))
rmst0.dbp <- lapply(df.list.dbp, function(x) rmst2(x$I9_HYPTENS_AGE, x$I9_HYPTENS, x$CAT, tau=95))

Results are extracted for the table

Following results are collected: mean differences, ci’s, pvalues, mean times and their confidence intervals.

#Results extracted:
#

names = c("SBP", "DBP")
rmsts = list(rmst0.sbp, rmst0.dbp)

rmst.diff  <- my_rmst_diffs(names,rmsts) 
rmst.means <- my_rmst_means(names,rmsts)

Formatting the tables:

#This takes average of reference values in paiwise runs - which is unnecessary, because with the fixed tau the values are the same.
rmst.means.2080 <- 
  rbind(
    c("SBP", "20-80%", mean(sapply(rmst0.sbp, function(x) x$RMST.arm0$rmst[1]))),
    c("DBP", "20-80%", mean(sapply(rmst0.dbp, function(x) x$RMST.arm0$rmst[1])))
  ) %>%
  as.tibble() %>%
  rename(name=V1, q=V2, mean=V3)


#We need to add quantile 20 % -80 % to right place 
names.for.rmst <- 
  rbind(cbind("SBP", levels(df$SBP_CAT)), 
        cbind("DBP", levels(df$DBP_CAT))) %>%
  as.tibble() %>%
  rename(name = V1, q = V2) 

#Let us combine everything as one table:

rmst.table <- 
  
  names.for.rmst %>%
  left_join(rmst.diff, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  left_join(rmst.means, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  left_join(rmst.means.2080, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  mutate(mean = ifelse(is.na(mean.x), mean.y, mean.x),
         lower_mean = if_else(is.na(lower_mean), mean, lower_mean),
         upper_mean = if_else(is.na(upper_mean), mean, upper_mean)) %>%
  select(-mean.x, -mean.y) %>%
  my_tidy_table("0", 1) %>%
  mutate(est = if_else(q=="20-80%", "0", est)) %>%
  add_row(name="SBP", q="SBP", est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 1) %>%
  add_row(name="",    q="",    est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 7) %>%
  add_row(name="DBP", q="DBP", est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 8)
 

#rmst.table divided to two and formatted for forestplot

rmst.table.text <- rmst.table %>%
  select(q, est, pval) %>%
  add_row(q=NA, est="Mean difference (95% CI)", pval="P-value", .before = 1)
  
rmst.table.means <- rmst.table %>%
  select(mean, lower_mean, upper_mean) %>%
  rename(lower = lower_mean, upper=upper_mean) %>%
  add_row(mean=NA, lower=NA, upper=NA, .before = 1)

4 Restricted mean survival times

4.1 All data

Pairwise statistics between reference risk (20-80% quantile) and each other quantile is are calculated. For this purpose we need separate dataframe for each statistic of interest.

Creating dataframes for each cases:

#Run with covariates stalled - only unadjusted analysis is shown.

q <- c("<2.5%", "2.5-20%", "80-97.5%", ">97.5%" )
df.list.cvd  <-  lapply(q, my_extr_cats, endpoints=c("I9_CVD_HARD_AGE", "I9_CVD_HARD"), cat="SBP_CAT", df=df)
df.list.chd  <-  lapply(q, my_extr_cats, endpoints=c("I9_CHD_AGE", "I9_CHD"), cat="SBP_CAT", df=df)
df.list.str  <-  lapply(q, my_extr_cats, endpoints=c("I9_STR_AGE", "I9_STR"), cat="SBP_CAT", df=df)

rmst2 is runned for all cases

Unadjusted analysis - with covariates R stalls. Propably too large dataset. [The new version of package faster]

#Unadjusted, this works:

rmst0.cvd <- lapply(df.list.cvd, function(x) rmst2(x$I9_CVD_HARD_AGE, x$I9_CVD_HARD, x$CAT, tau=95))
rmst0.chd <- lapply(df.list.chd, function(x) rmst2(x$I9_CHD_AGE, x$I9_CHD, x$CAT, tau=95))
rmst0.str  <- lapply(df.list.str, function(x) rmst2(x$I9_STR_AGE, x$I9_STR, x$CAT, tau=95))

Results are extracted for the table

Following results are collected: mean differences, ci’s, pvalues, mean times and their confidence intervals.

#Results extracted:
#

names = c("CVD", "CHD", "STR")
rmsts = list(rmst0.cvd, rmst0.chd, rmst0.str)

rmst.diffs.cvd  <- my_rmst_diffs(names,rmsts) 
rmst.means.cvd <- my_rmst_means(names,rmsts)

Formatting the tables:

#This takes average of reference values in paiwise runs - which is unnecessary, because with the fixed tau the values are the same.
rmst.means.2080.cvd <- 
  rbind(
    c("CVD", "20-80%", mean(sapply(rmst0.cvd, function(x) x$RMST.arm0$rmst[1]))),
    c("CHD", "20-80%", mean(sapply(rmst0.chd, function(x) x$RMST.arm0$rmst[1]))),
    c("STR", "20-80%", mean(sapply(rmst0.str, function(x) x$RMST.arm0$rmst[1])))
  ) %>%
  as.tibble() %>%
  rename(name=V1, q=V2, mean=V3)


#We need to add quantile 20 % -80 % to right place 
names.for.rmst.cvd <- 
  rbind(cbind("CVD", levels(df$SBP_CAT)), 
        cbind("CHD", levels(df$SBP_CAT)), 
        cbind("STR", levels(df$SBP_CAT))) %>%
  as.tibble() %>%
  rename(name = V1, q = V2) 

#Let us combine everything as one table:

rmst.table <- 
  
  names.for.rmst.cvd %>%
  left_join(rmst.diffs.cvd, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  left_join(rmst.means.cvd, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  left_join(rmst.means.2080.cvd, by=c("name", "q")) %>%
  mutate(mean = ifelse(is.na(mean.x), mean.y, mean.x),
         lower_mean = if_else(is.na(lower_mean), mean, lower_mean),
         upper_mean = if_else(is.na(upper_mean), mean, upper_mean)) %>%
  select(-mean.x, -mean.y) %>%
  my_tidy_table("0", 1) %>%
  mutate(est = if_else(q=="20-80%", "0", est)) %>%
  add_row(name="CVD", q="CVD", est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 1) %>%
  add_row(name="",    q="",    est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 7) %>%
  add_row(name="CHD", q="CHD", est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,  .before = 8) %>%
  add_row(name="",    q="",    est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,   .before = 14)%>%
  add_row(name="Stroke", q="Stroke", est="", pval="", lower_mean=NA, upper_mean=NA, mean=NA,   .before = 15)
 

#rmst.table divided to two and formatted for forestplot

rmst.table.text.cvd <- rmst.table %>%
  select(q, est, pval) %>%
  add_row(q=NA, est="Mean difference (95% CI)", pval="P-value", .before = 1)
  
rmst.table.means.cvd <- rmst.table %>%
  select(mean, lower_mean, upper_mean) %>%
  rename(lower = lower_mean, upper=upper_mean) %>%
  add_row(mean=NA, lower=NA, upper=NA, .before = 1)
